I have created both `hypothesis.md` and `candidate.py` as requested.

The hypothesis is a direct refinement of the current best-fitting model (`inner_loop_model`). While the existing model accounts for the central cognitive mechanism (that people paradoxically perceive sequence imbalance as being more random), it strictly enforces symmetric judgments. The new hypothesis introduces a widely applicable mechanism in choice tasks: a baseline spatial/presentation order preference (side bias), predicting that users have an underlying propensity to pick the first (left) sequence, independent of its content. 

This model introduces a `side_bias` free parameter (sampled from a Normal prior centered at zero) which is added alongside the main heuristic within the sigmoid choice function, fully preserving numerical safety inside PyMC.
